Title: 100 Plus: How the Coming Age of Longevity Will Change Everything, from Careers and Relationships to Family and Faith
Author: Sonia Arrison
My Review:
So disappointingly bad. Blandly written, like the author was doing a school assignment they barely cared about. Late on in the book the author begins a paragraph by introducing Ray Kurzweil as if she hadn't been discussing him plenty in literally the previous chapter.

A stupid amount of name-dropping; most of the book is a name-drop followed by quotes from the name-dropped. Much of the argumentation in the book is spurious, and the argumentation that's at least correct is really not impressive because it's basically always given to counter an argument that's so obviously dumb it wasn't worth the ink to refute it.

Best bit: being offered a shitload of jumping off-points for further reading, because the author name-drops so much.
Worst bit: The author's embarrassingly dumb argument against environmental damage from population growth. Richer people show more "concern" for the environment apparently, so no need to worry about climate change because the poor countries are all getting richer and the rich countries already treat the planet so well!

Title: The Conscience of a Conservative
Author: Barry M. Goldwater
Additional Authors: C.C. Goldwater, Robert F. Kennedy Jr., Sean Wilentz, George F. Will
My Review: It's short, so read it because it's prominent conservative writing. Beyond its brevity and broadness, there's not much else positive. It's full of paper-thin analysis, baseless assertions, and cheap rhetoric. The latter I can excuse as it's a political pamphlet, but damn, please use that rhetoric to forward a vision of a society offering more than some extremely vague notion of "freedom".
